Right. You want the Wikipedia article on the World Wide Web, but… more. You want it to have a pulse, a shadow. Fine. Don’t expect me to hold your hand through it. This is what you get.

***

### World Wide Web

This article is about the global system of pages accessed via [HTTP](/HTTP). For the worldwide computer network itself, you’re looking for [Internet](/Internet). And if you’re lost and need a browser, try [WorldWideWeb](/WorldWideWeb) – though I doubt it’s still in fashion.

"WWW" and "The Web"—yes, they redirect here. Don't get cute with me. If you need disambiguation, try [WWW (disambiguation)](/WWW_(disambiguation)) or [The Web (disambiguation)](/The_Web_(disambiguation)).

**World Wide Web**
**Abbreviation:** WWW, W3, The Web
**Status:** Active
**Year started:** 1989 (36 years ago)
**First published:** 6 August 1991 (34 years ago)
**Organization:**
*   [CERN](/CERN) (1989–1994)
*   [W3C](/W3C) (1994–current)
**Authors:** [Tim Berners-Lee](/Tim_Berners-Lee)

Here’s a [web page](/Web_page) from [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia), rendered, I assume, by [Google Chrome](/Google_Chrome). Riveting.

The World Wide Web, or WWW, or W3, or just… the Web, is this sprawling [information system](/Information_system). It lets you share content over the [Internet](/Internet) in ways that, thankfully, don’t require you to be a [computer scientist](/IT) or some basement-dwelling hobbyist. [1] [2] It’s all about accessing documents and other [web resources](/Web_resource) through the Internet, using a specific set of rules called the [Hypertext Transfer Protocol](/HTTP) (HTTP). [3]

[Tim Berners-Lee](/Tim_Berners-Lee), an English chap, cooked it up at [CERN](/CERN) back in 1989. It finally opened its doors to the public in 1993. His vision? A "universal linked information system." [4] [5] [6] [Web servers](/Web_server) dish out documents and media, and programs like [web browsers](/Web_browser) slurp them up. Everything on the Web has an address, a [uniform resource locator](/Uniform_resource_locator) (URL), so you can find it.

The original, and still the most common, format is the [web page](/Web_page), written in [Hypertext Markup Language](/Hypertext_Markup_Language) (HTML). HTML can handle plain text, [images](/Digital_image), [video](/Video), [audio](/Audio_signal), and even little [scripts](/Scripting_language) to make things interactive. And, of course, there are [hyperlinks](/Hyperlink)—those embedded URLs that whisk you away to other resources. This whole dance of following links is what they call [web navigation](/Web_navigation), or web surfing. If you want to get fancy, these pages can function as [web applications](/Web_application), essentially [application software](/Application_software). All this information travels across the Internet via HTTP. A collection of related resources, usually under the same [domain name](/Domain_name), forms a [website](/Website). One server can host many sites, and the biggest sites? They’re spread across countless servers. The content itself comes from everywhere: companies, governments, individuals. It’s a colossal, chaotic repository of everything from education to entertainment.

The Web has become the dominant [information systems platform](/Web_platform) on the planet. [7] [8] [9] [10] It’s how billions of us actually interact with the Internet. [3]

### History

• Main article: [History of the World Wide Web](/History_of_the_World_Wide_Web)

This [NeXT Computer](/NeXT_Computer), the one [Sir Tim Berners-Lee](/Sir_Tim_Berners-Lee) used at [CERN](/CERN), was the world’s first [Web server](/Web_server). Quite the artifact.

So, [Tim Berners-Lee](/Tim_Berners-Lee), again, working at [CERN](/CERN). He was drowning in documents, data, and collaborators. Finding, updating, and distributing this mess was a nightmare. He looked at existing systems – the [tree structure](/Tree_(computing)) of [Unix](/Unix_filesystem), the keyword tagging of VAX/NOTES – and found them wanting. He’d already tinkered with a private system called [ENQUIRE](/ENQUIRE) at CERN in 1980. Then he stumbled upon [Ted Nelson](/Ted_Nelson)'s [hypertext](/Hypertext) ideas from 1965, where documents could be linked willy-nilly through "hot spots." This confirmed his own direction. [13] [14]

The historic World Wide Web logo, designed by [Robert Cailliau](/Robert_Cailliau). You won't see it much anymore.

Later, [Apple](/Apple_Computer) made hypertext popular with [HyperCard](/HyperCard). But Berners-Lee’s vision was grander from the start: links across independent computers, accessible by anyone on the Internet. He also envisioned handling more than just text – graphics, sound, video. Links could point to data files or even trigger programs on the server. He planned "gateways" to access other systems, like traditional [file systems](/File_system) or [Usenet](/Usenet). Crucially, he insisted on decentralization. No single entity in control. [5] [15] [11] [12]

Berners-Lee pitched his proposal to CERN in May 1989. No name yet. By the end of 1990, he had a working system: a browser called [WorldWideWeb](/WorldWideWeb) (which also became the project's name and the network's name), and an HTTP server running at CERN. He defined the first HTTP protocol, the basic URL structure, and essentially cemented HTML as the primary document format. [16] It trickled out to other institutions in early 1991 and then, on August 23, 1991, to the entire Internet. It caught on, slowly at first, spreading through scientific and academic circles. Within two years, there were already [50 websites](/List_of_websites_founded_before_1995). [17] [18]

CERN did everyone a favor and made the Web’s code and protocols available for free on April 30, 1993. That’s when things really took off. [19] [20] [21] Then came [Mosaic](/Mosaic_(web_browser)), released by the [NCSA](/National_Center_for_Supercomputing_Applications) later that year. It was graphical, could display images *inline*, and handle forms. Suddenly, the Web was accessible. [Thousands of websites](/List_of_websites_founded_before_1995) sprouted within a year. [22] [23] [Marc Andreessen](/Marc_Andreessen) and [Jim Clark](/James_H._Clark) founded [Netscape](/Netscape) the next year, giving us the [Navigator browser](/Netscape_Navigator). They threw in [Java](/Java_(programming_language)) and [JavaScript](/JavaScript), and it dominated. Netscape’s [IPO](/Initial_public_offering) in 1995 kicked off the [dot-com bubble](/Dot-com_bubble). Microsoft’s answer? [Internet Explorer](/Internet_Explorer), bundled with Windows, which held the crown for 14 years. [27] [26]

Berners-Lee, meanwhile, started the [World Wide Web Consortium](/World_Wide_Web_Consortium) (W3C). They churned out [XML](/XML) in 1996 and pushed for [XHTML](/XHTML) to replace HTML. But the browser developers, particularly those pushing [Ajax](/Ajax_(programming)) with [XMLHttpRequest](/XMLHttpRequest), had other ideas. [Mozilla](/Mozilla), [Opera](/Opera_(company)), and Apple backed the [WHATWG](/WHATWG), which championed [HTML5](/HTML5). The W3C eventually conceded, abandoning XHTML in 2009 and handing over HTML specification control to WHATWG in 2019. [29] [30] [31]

The Web, in essence, became the engine of the [Information Age](/Information_Age), the primary way billions connect online. [32] [33] [34] [10]

### Nomenclature

Tim Berners-Lee himself insists it’s "World Wide Web," three separate words, no hyphens, all caps. [35] The "www" prefix, though, is fading. We’re more likely to say "Gmail" or "Facebook" than "www.gmail.com." As the [mobile web](/Mobile_web) exploded, [36] those prefixes became cumbersome. [37]

In English, it’s usually "double-u double-u double-u." New Zealanders apparently prefer "dub-dub-dub." [38] [39] And [Douglas Adams](/Douglas_Adams) once quipped, "The World Wide Web is the only thing I know of whose shortened form takes three times longer to say than what it's short for." [41] Wise words.

### Function

• Main articles: [HTTP](/HTTP) and [HTML](/HTML)

Think of the World Wide Web as an [application layer](/Application_layer) [protocol](/Communications_protocol) running *on* the Internet, making it actually useful. [Mosaic](/Mosaic_(web_browser)) was the spark that lit the fire, making the Web visually appealing with inline images and such.

People often conflate the Internet and the World Wide Web. They’re not the same. The Internet is the global network of [computer networks](/Computer_network), the physical infrastructure. The Web is the collection of documents and resources on that network, linked by [URIs](/Uniform_Resource_Identifier) and accessed via HTTP or HTTPS. [3]

To view a [web page](/Web_page), you either type its [URL](/Uniform_resource_locator) into a browser or click a [hyperlink](/Hyperlink). The browser then embarks on a silent ballet of requests and responses to fetch and display the page. In the 90s, this process was dubbed "browsing" or "web surfing." Early studies tried to categorize this new behavior, identifying patterns like "exploratory surfing" and "targeted navigation." [42]

Let’s take `http://example.org/home.html` as an example. Your browser first needs to translate `example.org` into an [Internet Protocol address](/IP_address) using the [Domain Name System](/Domain_Name_System) (DNS). Say it gets `203.0.113.4`. Then, it sends an [HTTP](/Hypertext_Transfer_Protocol) request across the Internet to that address, specifically to port 80 (or 443 for HTTPS). The request itself is simple:

```
GET /home.html HTTP/1.1
Host: example.org
```

The server at `example.org` receives this on port 80 and, if it can fulfill the request, sends back a response:

```
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8
```

Followed by the actual HTML content of the page. A basic HTML page might look like this:

```html
<html>
<head>
<title>Example.org – The World Wide Web</title>
</head>
<body>
<p>The World Wide Web, abbreviated as WWW and commonly known ...</p>
</body>
</html>
```

Your browser then [parses](/Parsing) this HTML, interpreting tags like `<title>` and `<p>` to format the text. Often, HTML pages reference other resources: images, scripts, [Cascading Style Sheets](/Cascading_Style_Sheets) for layout. The browser makes *more* HTTP requests for these. As it receives them, it progressively [renders](/Browser_engine) the page.

#### HTML

• Main article: [HTML](/HTML)

[Hypertext Markup Language](/Hypertext_Markup_Language) (HTML) is the bedrock of [web pages](/Web_page) and [web applications](/Web_application). It’s the first part of the cornerstone trio: HTML, CSS, and [JavaScript](/JavaScript). [43]

Browsers fetch HTML from a [web server](/Web_server) or local storage and render it into what you see. HTML defines the page's structure [semantically](/Semantic_Web) and, originally, hinted at its appearance.

[HTML elements](/HTML_element) are the fundamental building blocks. They can embed [images](/HTML_element), [forms](/Fieldset), and more. HTML structures text with headings, paragraphs, lists, [links](/Hyperlink), and so on, using tags enclosed in [angle brackets](/Bracket). Tags like `<img />` and `<input />` insert content directly. Others, like `<p>`, wrap around text to define its meaning. Browsers don't show the tags; they use them to interpret the page.

HTML can also embed [scripting languages](/Scripting_language) like [JavaScript](/JavaScript) to control page behavior and content. [Cascading Style Sheets](/Cascading_Style_Sheets) dictate the look and layout. The [World Wide Web Consortium](/World_Wide_Web_Consortium) (W3C) has been pushing CSS over explicit HTML styling since 1997. [44]

#### Linking

Most web pages are riddled with [hyperlinks](/Hyperlink) to other pages, files, definitions—whatever. In HTML, a link looks like this:

`<a href="http://example.org/home.html">Example.org Homepage</a>`

![Graphic representation of a minute fraction of the WWW, demonstrating hyperlinks](/Hyperlink)

This interconnected web of information is, well, the World Wide Web. Tim Berners-Lee first called it the WorldWideWeb in November 1990, using [CamelCase](/CamelCase) that’s since been dropped. [45]

The structure of these links forms a [webgraph](/Webgraph), where nodes are pages and edges are links. But links break. Resources vanish. Content changes. This is ["link rot"](/Link_rot). Efforts like the [Internet Archive](/Internet_Archive), active since 1996, try to preserve this ephemeral landscape.

#### www prefix

Many web hostnames start with "www." It’s a convention, like naming an [FTP server](/FTP_server) "ftp" or a [Usenet](/Usenet) server "news." These are [subdomains](/Subdomain) within the [Domain Name System](/Domain_Name_System) (DNS), like `www.example.com`. It’s not a rule, though. The very first web server was `nxoc01.cern.ch`. [46] Apparently, the "www" subdomain was an accident; the project page was meant for `www.cern.ch`, but the DNS records were never swapped. [47] [better source needed] Many sites use `www` or `www2`, `secure`, or `en` for specific functions. Sometimes `example.com` and `www.example.com` point to the same place; sometimes they don't. Using subdomains is useful for [load balancing](/Load_balancing_(computing)) by pointing a [CNAME record](/CNAME_record) to a cluster of servers. You can’t do that with the bare domain root. [48] [dubious – discuss]

Some browsers, if you type in an incomplete domain, will automatically try adding "www." and common suffixes like ".com" or ".org." Entering "microsoft" might become `http://www.microsoft.com/`. This feature appeared in early [Firefox](/Firefox) versions. [49] [unreliable source?] Microsoft apparently patented something similar for mobile devices. [50]

#### Scheme specifiers

The `http://` and `https://` at the start of a [URI](/Uniform_Resource_Identifier) tell your browser which protocol to use: the standard [Hypertext Transfer Protocol](/Hypertext_Transfer_Protocol) or its encrypted sibling, [HTTP Secure](/HTTP_Secure). HTTPS is crucial for sensitive data like passwords and bank details. Browsers often assume `http://` if you forget it. [citation needed]

### Pages

• Main article: [Web page](/Web_page)

A [web page](/Web_browser) is, quite simply, a document meant for the World Wide Web and its browsers. It’s what you see on your [monitor](/Computer_display) or [mobile device](/Mobile_device).

"Web page" usually means what’s visible, but it can also refer to the [computer file](/Computer_file) itself, typically a [text file](/Text_file) with [hypertext](/Hypertext) markup, usually [HTML](/HTML). Pages contain [hyperlinks](/Hyperlink) to other pages. Browsers often need to fetch multiple [web resources](/Web_resource)—[style sheets](/Cascading_Style_Sheets), [scripts](/Client-side_scripting), images—to display a single page.

On a network, browsers retrieve pages from a remote [web server](/Web_server). This server might be private, like on a corporate [intranet](/Intranet). The browser uses [HTTP](/Hypertext_Transfer_Protocol) to ask for these pages.

There are two main types: static and dynamic.

#### Static page

• Main article: [Static web page](/Static_web_page)

A static web page—or flat page, stationary page—is delivered exactly as it's stored. No [web application](/Web_application) generating it on the fly. [120]

This means it shows the same thing to everyone, unless the server is configured to serve different language or content-type versions.

#### Dynamic pages

• Main articles: [Dynamic web page](/Dynamic_web_page) and [Ajax (programming)](/Ajax_(programming))

A dynamic page is shaped by server-side scripts. [PHP](/PHP) and [MySQL](/MySQL) are common tools here. [Parameters](/Parameter_(computer_programming)) dictate how the page is assembled for each request.

Client-side dynamic pages use JavaScript running in the browser to modify the page's [Document Object Model](/Document_Object_Model) (DOM). This can happen without a full page reload, especially with [Ajax](/Ajax_(programming)) techniques. Ajax allows a single page to update its content dynamically, making it feel more like an application than a static document. This often means your [web browsing history](/Web_browsing_history) isn't updated in the traditional sense for those specific dynamic updates.

Dynamic HTML, or DHTML, was an umbrella term for these technologies, though [AJAX](/Ajax_(programming)) has largely superseded it. Client-side scripts, server-side scripts, or both, create the dynamic experience. [citation needed]

[JavaScript](/JavaScript), created by [Brendan Eich](/Brendan_Eich) at [Netscape](/Netscape) in 1995, is the language of choice for interactivity. [51] The standardized version is [ECMAScript](/ECMAScript). [51] Ajax, using asynchronous JavaScript and [XML](/XML), allows pages to fetch data from the server without interrupting the user. Scripts can make HTTP requests, modify the page's DOM, or even [poll](/Polling_(computer_science)) the server for updates. [52]

### Website

The [usap.gov](/United_States_Antarctic_Program) website. Just… a website.

• Main article: [Website](/Website)

A [website](/URL) is basically a collection of related [web pages](/Web_page) and [multimedia](/Multimedia) content, all tied together by a common [domain name](/Domain_name) and hosted on at least one [web server](/Web_server). Think [wikipedia.org](/Wikipedia), [google.com](/Google), [amazon.com](/Amazon_(company)).

You access them via the public [Internet Protocol](/Internet_Protocol) (IP) network, the [Internet](/Internet), or a private [local area network](/Local_area_network) (LAN), using a [uniform resource locator](/URL).

Websites serve countless purposes: personal pages, corporate sites, government portals, organization hubs. They’re usually focused on a specific topic—entertainment, [social networking](/Social_networking), news, education. All the publicly accessible ones make up the World Wide Web. Private ones, like a company’s internal site, are part of an [intranet](/Intranet).

[Web pages](/HTML) are built with [plain text](/Plain_text) and [formatting instructions](/Formatted_text) like [HTML](/HTML) or [XHTML](/XHTML). They can pull in elements from other sites. Accessing them involves [HTTP](/Hypertext_Transfer_Protocol), sometimes secured with [HTTPS](/HTTP_Secure). Your [web browser](/Web_browser) then interprets the markup and displays it.

[Hyperlinking](/Hyperlink) guides you through the site, often starting at the [home page](/Home_page). Some sites require registration or [subscription](/Subscription). Think news sites, academic journals, gaming platforms, [message boards](/Internet_forum), webmail, [social networking](/Social_networking) sites. You can access them on anything from a [desktop computer](/Desktop_computer) to a [smartphone](/Smartphone).

#### Browser

• Main article: [Web browser](/Web_browser)

A web browser, or just "browser," is the [software](/Software_application) you use to navigate the Web. It’s your [user agent](/User_agent). You need one to connect to a server and display its pages. It handles downloading, formatting, and rendering.

Besides finding and displaying pages, browsers usually offer bookmarks, history, cookie management, and home pages. Some even remember your passwords.

The big players right now? [Chrome](/Google_Chrome), [Safari](/Safari_(web_browser)), [Edge](/Microsoft_Edge), [Samsung Internet](/Samsung_Internet), and [Firefox](/Firefox). [54]

#### Server

• Main article: [Web server](/Web_server)

This is a [Dell PowerEdge](/Dell_PowerEdge) server. Looks important.

A Web server is the [server software](/Server_software), or the hardware running it, that responds to World Wide Web client requests. It can host one or many websites. It speaks [HTTP](/Hypertext_Transfer_Protocol) and related protocols.

Its main job is to store, process, and deliver [web pages](/Web_page) to [clients](/Client_(computing)). [55] Communication happens via HTTP. The delivered content is usually [HTML documents](/HTML), but can include [images](/Image), [style sheets](/Style_sheet_(web_development)), and [scripts](/JavaScript).

For high-traffic sites, multiple servers work together. These are [Dell](/Dell) servers, powering the [Wikimedia Foundation](/Wikimedia_Foundation).

Your [web browser](/Web_browser) or [web crawler](/Web_crawler) sends an HTTP request. The server responds with the requested content or an [error message](/List_of_HTTP_status_codes). The content is usually a file on the server's [secondary storage](/Secondary_memory), but not always.

Servers can also receive data from clients, used for [web forms](/Form_(web)) and file uploads.

Many servers support [scripting languages](/Server-side_scripting) like [ASP](/Active_Server_Pages) or [PHP](/PHP). This means the server's behavior can be customized without changing the core software. This is often used to generate [HTML documents](/HTML) [dynamically](/Dynamic_web_page) on the fly, rather than serving [static documents](/Static_web_page). Dynamic generation is slower but essential for personalized content, often pulling data from [databases](/Database). Static is faster and easier to [cache](/Web_cache).

Servers are also embedded in smaller devices—[printers](/Printer_(computing)), [routers](/Router_(computing)), [webcams](/Webcam)—often serving only a [local network](/Local_area_network) for administration. This means you only need a browser, which is usually built into your [operating system](/Operating_system).

### Optical Networking

[Optical networking](/Optical_networking) is the backbone of modern communication, using fiber optics to transmit data globally. It relies on complex components like [tunable lasers](/Tunable_laser), filters, and switches to manage these high-speed networks. [56] [57]

The vast network of optical fiber laid down in the late 20th century underpins the Internet. This "information highway" uses light pulses to carry data. [58]

Early iterations like the [ARPANET](/ARPANET), established in 1969, connected universities and researchers. [59] [60] [61] [62] But access was restricted. The [National Science Foundation](/National_Science_Foundation) created the [NSFNET](/National_Science_Foundation_Network) in 1985 to provide broader supercomputer access. [62]

Public demand for Internet access grew, leading to pressure for privatization. In 1993, the [National Information Infrastructure Act](/National_Information_Infrastructure) mandated the NSF to transfer control to commercial entities. [63] [64]

The privatization and the public release of the World Wide Web in 1993 triggered an explosion in demand. Developers scrambled to find ways to increase data transmission speeds and reduce costs, like improving fiber capacity. [65] [66] [67] [68]

In 1994, Pirelli’s optical division introduced a wavelength-division multiplexing (WDM) system, allowing more data to be sent simultaneously over a single fiber. [69] [70]

[Ciena Corporation](/Ciena), founded by [David Huber](/David_R._Huber) and [Kevin Kimberlin](/Kevin_Kimberlin) in 1992, also developed WDM technology. Drawing on laser expertise, Ciena focused on optical amplifiers. [71] [72] [73] Their dual-stage amplifier for dense WDM (DWDM) was patented in 1997 and deployed by Sprint in 1996. [77] [78] [79] [80] [81]

### Cookie

• Main article: [HTTP cookie](/HTTP_cookie)

An HTTP cookie, or web cookie, is a small piece of data sent from a website and stored by your browser. They were designed to remember things: items in a shopping cart, login status, browsing activity. They can even store information you’ve typed into forms.

Cookies are essential for the modern web. Authentication cookies, for instance, tell servers if you're logged in. Without them, sites couldn't send you sensitive data or ask you to log in. Cookie security depends on the website and browser, and whether the data is encrypted. Weaknesses can lead to data theft or unauthorized access, as seen in [cross-site scripting](/Cross-site_scripting) and [cross-site request forgery](/Cross-site_request_forgery) attacks. [82]

Tracking cookies, especially third-party ones, raise [privacy concerns](/Internet_privacy) by compiling long-term browsing histories. This prompted legislation in Europe and the US. [83] [84] [85] EU law requires informed consent for storing non-essential cookies.

Jann Horn of Google's [Project Zero](/Project_Zero_(Google)) highlighted how cookies can be intercepted by network intermediaries. He recommends using [private browsing](/Private_browsing) mode (like [Incognito mode](/Incognito_mode)) in such cases. [86]

### Search engine

• Main article: [Search engine](/Search_engine)

Results from a web [image search](/Image_search) engine for "lunar eclipse." Fascinating.

A web search engine is a [software system](/Software_system) designed to systematically search the World Wide Web for information based on a [web search query](/Web_search_query). Results are typically presented as a list, often called [search engine results pages](/Search_engine_results_page) (SERPs). These can include [web pages](/Web_page), images, videos, and more. Some engines also mine [databases](/Database) or [web directories](/Web_directory). Unlike human-edited directories, search engines use [algorithms](/Algorithm) run by [web crawlers](/Web_crawler) to maintain real-time information. Content not indexed by these engines is the [deep web](/Deep_web).

[Archie](/Archie_(search_engine)), the first search engine, launched in 1990. It indexed [File Transfer Protocol](/File_Transfer_Protocol) (FTP) sites. [87] [88] More advanced engines like [Yahoo!](/Yahoo!) (1995) and [Google](/Google_Search) (1998) followed. [89] [90]

#### Deep web

• Main article: [Deep web](/Deep_web)

The deep web, invisible web, or hidden web—these are the parts of the World Wide Web not indexed by standard search engines. [91] [92] [93] The opposite is the [surface web](/Surface_web). [94] Computer scientist Michael K. Bergman coined "deep web" in 2001. [95]

Deep web content is hidden behind [HTTP](/HTTP) forms [96] [97] and includes common services like [web mail](/Web_mail), [online banking](/Online_banking), and paid content behind [paywalls](/Paywall), such as [video on demand](/Video_on_demand).

You can access deep web content with a direct [URL](/URL) or [IP address](/IP_address), but it often requires a password or other authentication.

### Caching

A [web cache](/Web_cache) is a server that stores recently accessed web pages to speed up responses for repeated requests. Browsers also have [browser caches](/Browser_cache) for local storage. Browsers can request only changed data. Pages can specify expiration times to control caching, especially for sensitive data like in [online banking](/Online_banking). Website designers often group resources like CSS and JavaScript into single files for efficient caching. Enterprise [firewalls](/Firewall_(networking)) can cache web resources for multiple users. Some [search engines](/Search_engines) cache frequently accessed sites.

### Security

The Web is a playground for [criminals](/Criminal). [Malware](/Malware), [identity theft](/Identity_theft), [fraud](/Fraud), [espionage](/Espionage)—it’s all here. [98] Web-based vulnerabilities now surpass traditional computer security issues. [99] [100] Google estimates about 10% of web pages contain malicious code. [101] Most attacks happen on legitimate sites, often hosted in the US, China, and Russia, according to [Sophos](/Sophos). [102] [SQL injection](/SQL_injection) is the most common malware threat. [103] HTML and URIs opened the door to attacks like [cross-site scripting](/Cross-site_scripting) (XSS) with the rise of JavaScript, [104] further amplified by [Web 2.0](/Web_2.0) and Ajax. [105] In 2007, an estimated 70% of websites were vulnerable to XSS. [106] [Phishing](/Phishing) is another major threat; global losses were estimated at $1.5 billion in 2012. [107] Covert and Open Redirects are common phishing tactics.

Solutions vary. Security companies like [McAfee](/McAfee) offer compliance tools. [Finjan Holdings](/Finjan_Holdings) advocates real-time inspection of code. [98] Some see security as a business opportunity, not a cost. [109] Others call for "ubiquitous, always-on [digital rights management](/Digital_rights_management)" infrastructure. [110] [Jonathan Zittrain](/Jonathan_Zittrain) believes shared user responsibility for security is better than locking down the Internet. [111]

### Privacy

• Main article: [Internet privacy](/Internet_privacy)

Every time you request a page, the server sees your [IP address](/IP_address). Servers log these. Browsers usually keep a history and [cache](/Web_cache) content locally. If your connection isn't encrypted with HTTPS, your requests travel in plain text, visible to anyone in between. A [virtual private network](/Virtual_private_network) (VPN) can encrypt traffic and mask your IP, reducing tracking.

When you supply personal information—name, address, email—websites can link your traffic to you. Using [HTTP cookies](/HTTP_cookie), logins, or other trackers, they can connect current and past visits. This allows organizations to build detailed profiles—interests, profession, demographics. [Demographic profile](/Demographic_profile). These profiles are valuable to marketers and advertisers. Depending on terms of service and local laws, this data might be sold or shared. For most, it means targeted ads or spam. For some, it can lead to unwanted attention based on niche interests. Law enforcement and intelligence agencies can also track individuals.

[Social networking](/Social_networking) sites often encourage real names and details, believing it enhances engagement. However, uploaded photos or careless posts can be linked to individuals, sometimes with regret. Employers, schools, and family might see things you didn't intend them to. [Cyberbullies](/Cyberbullying) can exploit personal information for harassment or [stalking](/Cyberstalking). While privacy settings exist, they can be complex. Photos and videos pose particular issues, especially with advancing [facial recognition technology](/Facial_recognition_system). Removing content from the Web is nearly impossible due to caching and mirroring.

### Standards

• Main article: [Web standards](/Web_standards)

Web standards encompass specifications that govern the [Internet](/Internet) and the Web, affecting [interoperability](/Interoperability), [accessibility](/Accessibility), and [usability](/Usability).

They include:
*   Recommendations from the [World Wide Web Consortium](/World_Wide_Web_Consortium) (W3C). [113]
*   The "Living Standard" from the [Web Hypertext Application Technology Working Group](/Web_Hypertext_Application_Technology_Working_Group) (WHATWG).
*   [Request for Comments](/Request_for_Comments) (RFC) documents from the [Internet Engineering Task Force](/Internet_Engineering_Task_Force) (IETF). [114]
*   Standards from the [International Organization for Standardization](/International_Organization_for_Standardization) (ISO). [115]
*   Standards from [Ecma International](/Ecma_International). [116]
*   The [Unicode](/Unicode) Standard and reports from the [Unicode Consortium](/Unicode_Consortium). [117]
*   Registries maintained by the [Internet Assigned Numbers Authority](/Internet_Assigned_Numbers_Authority) (IANA). [118]

These standards evolve; they aren't static. They're developed by [standards organizations](/Standards_organization), not single entities. It’s important to distinguish draft specifications from finalized ones.

#### Accessibility

• Main article: [Web accessibility](/Web_accessibility)

Alternative methods and formats exist to make the Web accessible to people with [disabilities](/Disability)—visual, auditory, physical, cognitive, etc. These features also help those with temporary impairments or ageing users. [120] The W3C stresses that universal access is crucial for equal opportunity. [121] Tim Berners-Lee himself said, "The power of the Web is in its universality. Access by everyone regardless of disability is an essential aspect." [120] Many countries mandate web accessibility. [122] The W3C's [Web Accessibility Initiative](/Web_Accessibility_Initiative) provides guidelines for creators and developers to ensure the Web is usable by all, including those using [assistive technology](/Assistive_technology). [120] [123]

#### Internationalisation

• Main article: [Internationalisation and localization](/Internationalization_and_localization)

The W3C's [Internationalisation](/Internationalization_and_localization) Activity ensures web technologies work across languages, scripts, and cultures. [124] [Unicode](/Unicode) became dominant around 2007, surpassing [ASCII](/ASCII). [125] While original [RFC](/RFC_(identifier)) 3986 limited URIs to US-ASCII, [RFC 3987](/RFC_3987) allows any [Universal Character Set](/Universal_Character_Set) character, enabling [IRIs](/Internationalized_Resource_Identifier) in any language. [126]

